South African futures were marginally higher on Tuesday after the JSE closed in the red, as platinum and gold shares retreated for the second consecutive session.Mining stocks were under pressure ahead of an expected US interest-rate increase next week. Commodity prices softened despite Brent crude edging higher to $56 a barrel in early evening trade.The all share closed 0.23% lower at 51,377.80 points and the blue-chip top 40 shed 0.19%. The gold index closed 2.93% lower and platinums shed 2.24%. Food and drug retailers lost 1.2%, banks were 1.08% down and resources lost 0.79%.Property added 0.28%.The Dow was flat in early evening trade at just less than the 21,000 points mark. European markets were mixed, with the UK&rsquo;s FTSE 100 losing 0.07%. The French CAC 40 dropped 0.42% and the German Dax 30 gained 0.06%.At 5.50pm, the local near-dated top-40 Alsi futures index was 0.17% higher at 44,390 points with 18,891 contracts traded from Monday&rsquo;s 23,782.